  "prompt": "Can gravity slow time?",
  "response": "Yes, gravity can slow time, according to Albert Einstein's General Theory of Relativity. This effect is known as **gravitational time dilation**. Here\u2019s how it works:\n\n1. **Curvature of Spacetime**: Gravity is the result of the curvature of spacetime caused by mass. The more massive an object, the more it curves spacetime.\n\n2. **Time in a Gravitational Field**: Clocks run slower in stronger gravitational fields compared to those in weaker fields. This means that time passes more slowly near a massive object (like a planet or a black hole) than it does farther away from it.\n\n3. **Practical Example**: A clock on Earth\u2019s surface (where gravity is stronger) ticks more slowly than a clock on a satellite in orbit (where gravity is weaker). This effect is tiny but measurable, and it\u2019s taken into account in technologies like GPS.\n\n4. **Extreme Cases**: Near the event horizon of a black hole, where gravity is extremely intense, time slows down dramatically from the perspective of an outside observer.\n\nThis phenomenon has been experimentally confirmed through precise measurements, including experiments with atomic clocks at different altitudes and observations of light from distant stars bending near massive objects. It\u2019s a fundamental aspect of how gravity and time are intertwined in the fabric of spacetime.",
